    grammar: { title: `Quantifiers — Too, enough, too much, too many`, content: `These words describe quantity and degree. 'Too' means more than needed (negative): 'It's too expensive' (C'est trop cher). 'Enough' means sufficient: 'I have enough money' (J'ai assez d'argent). 'Not enough' means insufficient: 'I don't have enough time'. 'Too much' + uncountable: 'too much money, too much time'. 'Too many' + countable: 'too many people, too many problems'. 'Enough' goes AFTER adjectives: 'big enough, fast enough' — but BEFORE nouns: 'enough time, enough money'. A common mistake: 'enough big' is wrong — say 'big enough'.` },
