    grammar: { title: `Prepositions of place — in, on, at, by`, content: `Prepositions of place are tricky in English. Key rules: 'in' = inside an enclosed space: 'in the room', 'in Paris', 'in a box'. 'on' = on a surface or street: 'on the table', 'on Baker Street', 'on the first floor'. 'at' = a specific point or location: 'at the door', 'at school', 'at 23 Main Street'. Common expressions: 'at home', 'at work', 'at the office', 'in bed', 'in hospital' (British — no article), 'on the bus/train', 'on the phone', 'by the window' (next to), 'by the door'. Many of these are fixed phrases you just need to memorize.` },
