    grammar: { title: `Future tenses review — Organizing plans`, content: `When making plans in English, use the right future form. Present Continuous = confirmed plans with time/place: 'I'm meeting Jake on Saturday' (very certain, already arranged). Going to = intentions: 'I'm going to look for a new flat'. Will = spontaneous decisions or offers: 'I'll come with you!' Simple Present = scheduled/timetabled events: 'The train leaves at 8pm', 'The party starts at 7'. Quick guide: 'Are you coming?' (Are you planning to come — present continuous) is the most natural way to invite someone. 'Will you come?' sounds more formal or like you're asking for a commitment.` },
