    grammar: { title: `Intensifiers and downtoners — Amplifier ou atténuer`, content: `Intensifiers make adjectives stronger; downtoners weaken them. Strong intensifiers: absolutely, completely, totally, utterly, extremely, incredibly, awfully (= very). 'That was absolutely perfect', 'I'm completely exhausted'. Regular intensifiers: very, really, quite (AmE = very), pretty. Downtoners: a bit, a little, slightly, fairly, rather, somewhat, not that, not very. 'It's a bit cold', 'She's fairly good', 'I'm not that tired'. Note: 'quite' is tricky — in British English, 'quite good' often means 'fairly good' (not amazing), but in American English it means 'very good'. Context matters!` },
