    grammar: { title: `Linking and reduction in fast speech`, content: `In natural fast English, sounds blend together. Linking: when a word ends in a consonant and the next starts with a vowel, they blend: 'pick it up' → 'pickit up', 'turn it off' → 'turnit off'. Reduction: unstressed syllables get shorter: 'to' → /tə/, 'for' → /fər/, 'and' → /ən/, 'can' → /kən/. 'I can do it' → 'I /kən/ do it'. Elision: some sounds disappear: 'next day' → 'nex day', 'must be' → 'muss be'. This is why native speakers seem to speak fast — they're not speaking faster, they're linking and reducing sounds. The more you listen, the more you'll recognize these patterns.` },
